  "prompt": "Why does the Justin Bieber video Baby have more dislikes than likes?",
  "response": "The \"Baby\" music video by Justin Bieber, released in 2010, garnered a significant amount of attention and interaction, leading to both likes and dislikes. Reasons for the higher number of dislikes compared to likes might include:\n\n1. **Viral Fame and Backlash**: As one of the early viral hits in pop music, \"Baby\" attracted both fans and detractors. Some viewers may have disliked the song simply because it was ubiquitous and overplayed, leading to a backlash.\n\n2. **Target Audience**: Justin Bieber's music, particularly early in his career, often appealed to a younger demographic, and this sometimes alienated older listeners who may have voiced their opinions through dislikes.\n\n3. **Cultural Impact**: The song became a cultural phenomenon, and with such visibility often comes criticism. Many people who don\u2019t identify as fans might have added dislikes out of principle against mainstream pop music or the teen idol phenomenon.\n\n4. **Commentary Culture**: YouTube has a culture where highly popular videos can attract criticism and dislike votes as a form of commentary or protest against the mainstream music industry or the artist himself, regardless of musical quality.\n\n5. **Changes Over Time**: Over time, viewership dynamics can shift, leading to varying like/dislike ratios as audiences change their opinions based on trends or personal tastes.\n\nUltimately, while the video has a substantial number of dislikes, it also achieved massive popularity and helps illustrate the complexities of audience reception in the digital age.",
